from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Toledo,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Jorge, Manuel, Ramon, Rafael, Juan, Antonio, Jesus, Miguel, Roberto, Carlos, Francisco.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name from the city in central Spain, which was the capital of the Visigothic state between the 6th and 8th centuries. Its role declined for three centuries after the Muslim invasion of Spain, until it was taken as the capital of the kingdom of Castile between the 11th and 16th centuries. It was a major cultural and political center throughout the Middle Ages, and was also the home of an important Jewish community. The placename, first recorded in Latin as <i>Toletum</i>, is of obscure etymology, possibly connected with <i>Toleto</i> in Piedmont; Jewish tradition connects it with Hebrew <i>toledot</i> ‘generations’, but this is no more than folk etymology. Compare   Toledano  .","Jewish (Sephardic): also an adoption of the Spanish surname (see 1 above) at the moment of conversion to Roman Catholicism. After the return to Judaism (generations later), some descendants retained the surname their families used as Catholics."],"variants":[{"name":"Toledano","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Shlomo, Igal, Moshe, Shimon, Ehud, Shmuel, Yehuda.  Spanish Alberto, Gonzalo, Alina, Carlos, Conrado, Elena, Enrique, Evelia, Luis, Manuel, Miguel, Ramona.  French Gabrielle, Michel.","Spanish and Jewish (Sephardic): habitational name for someone from Toledo (see   Toledo  ), from an adjectival form of the placename."]}]},{"name":"Gutiérrez","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Jesus, Manuel, Carlos, Francisco, Jorge, Pedro, Raul, Miguel, Roberto.","Spanish (<b>Gutiérrez</b>): patronymic from the medieval personal name <i>Gutierre</i>, from a Visigothic personal name of uncertain form and meaning, perhaps a compound of the elements <i>gunthi</i> ‘battle’ + <i>hairus</i> ‘sword’."],"variants":[{"name":"Gutierez","meanings":["(1997: 130;2007: 1129; 2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Jose, Ignacio, Manuel, Adalberto, Ana Maria, Angel, Carlota, Emilio, Exiquio, Felipe, Fermin.","Hispanic (<b>Gutiérez</b>): altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Gutirrez","meanings":["(2007: 670; 2010: NA)","Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Guterrez","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Guiterrez","meanings":["(1997: 425;2007: 2304; 2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Luis, Arturo, Francisco, Alfredo, Jesus, Rafael, Raul, Carlos, Guadalupe, Jose Luis.","Hispanic (<b>Guitérrez</b>): altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Gutierres","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Ramon, Jesus, Juan, Manuel, Alberto, Alfonzo, Alvaro, Ana, Andres, Antelmo, Catalina.","Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Guitierez","meanings":["Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Guttierrez","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jesus, Jose, Pablo, Raul, Reina, Adolfo, Beatriz, Carlos, Diego, Evangelina, Felicita, Humberto.","Hispanic: altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]},{"name":"Guitierrez","meanings":["(1997: 110;2007: 1085; 2010: NA)","Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Juan, Enrique, Jaime, Manuel, Miguel, Ofelia, Ricardo, Salvador, Andres, Argentina, Armando.","Hispanic (<b>Guitiérrez</b>): altered form of Spanish <b>Gutiérrez</b> (see   Gutierrez  )."]}]}],"lif